Question 1

To estimate the probability a patient on TFD725+docetaxel will survive past 400 days within subgroups, the probability was first calculated by dividing the total number of patients within the age subgroup with the number of patients who survived past 400 days. We can get the estimated probability for the corresponding population values, for example the probability of survive for people who are within a certain age group under the treatment. In order to get the interval estimate, we can run 10000 simulations using the obtained probability and calculate the standard deviations from the simulations. Then by using the formula for calculating the 95% confidence interval, we can get the upper and lower bounds of the confidence intervals. Results are compiled within the data frame.

num_sim <- 10000
candidate_pi <- seq(from = 0, to = 1, 0.0001)
calc_sample_dist <- function(n,pi){
  nsamp <- 10000
  sample_counts <- rbinom(nsamp, n, pi)
  sample_means <- sample_counts/n
  return(sample_means)
}
getci.fuc <- function(a) {
####### calculate the probability of surviving past 400 within the subgroup
prob.x <- data.new %>%
  filter(subgroup == a) %>%
  summarise(prop = mean(survival.past.400)) %>%
    .$prop
###### calculating the number of patients within the subgroup
num.x <- data.new %>%
  filter(subgroup == a) %>%
  summarise(n=sum(tx))
num <- as.numeric(num.x)
##########
percentiles_pi <- function(num,pi) {
  samp_dist <- calc_sample_dist(num, pi)
  percentile <- mean(samp_dist <= prob.x) #both sides
  percentile
}
res.pi <- sapply(candidate_pi, percentiles_pi, n=num)
## Finding the upper and lower bounds ##
consistent_pi <- candidate_pi[(res.pi >= 0.025) & (res.pi <= 0.975)]
lower_bound <- min(consistent_pi)
upper_bound <- max(consistent_pi)
c(lower_bound, upper_bound)
}

Question 2

To evaluate whether the treatment is more effective than the control within each of the subgroups, we can first use boxplot and density graph to compare the mean observation time between the treatment and the control group, stratified for each age groups. From the boxplots for each of the age group, we can see that the mean observation time of the treatment are larger than the mean observation time of the control group for the five age groups. For age group 1, 3 and 5, we can see that the mean observation time is larger in the treatment group than in the control group, while for age group 2 and 5, the control group has higher mean observation time.

In order to test the hypothesis that the mean observation(survival) time under treatment is no greater than the mean observation(survival) time under control, we used permutation methods and calculated the tail probabilities for each age group. In theory, any permutation of the observations between the two treatments has the same chance to occur as any other permutation. And at the end we will compute the p-value as the proportion of mean survival time from permutation greater than or equal to the observed survival time. For each age group, we will conduct the same hypothesis test, and if p-value is less than or equal to the predetermined level of significance level of 0.05, we can reject the null hypothesis.

For age group 1, we can get one sided tail probability of 0.03, which means a p-value of 0.03 < 0.05, so we can reject the null hypothesis that the effects of treatment and control are the same within this age group. For age group 2, we can get the one-sided tail probability of 0.7, and a p value larger than 0.05 means that we cannot reject the null hypothesis that the effects of the treatment and the control are the same.From our observations from the boxplot, the treatment is actually inferior than the control in this age group. For age group 3, we can get the one-sided tail probability of 0.4, and a p value larger than 0.05 means that we cannot reject the null hypothesis that the effects of the treatment and the control are the same. For age group 4, we can get the one-sided tail probability of 0.06, and a p value larger than 0.05 means that we cannot reject the null hypothesis that the effects of the treatment and the control are the same. For age group 5, we can get the one-sided tail probability of 0.6, and a p value larger than 0.05 mean that we cannot reject the null hypothesis that the effects of the treatment and the control are the same. From our observations from the boxplot, the treatment is actually inferior than the control in this age group. The p-values are summarized in a table to better illustrate the results. From the results, we cannot reach the conclusion that the treatment TFD725+docetaxel is more effective than docetaxel alone for group 2 to 5, since we cannot reject the null that the treatment and control has the same mean observation time across the 4 age groups.

simulate.perm.trial <- function(data){

    ## create the permuted data ##
    perm <- sample(1:nrow(data), replace = FALSE) ## generating shuffled ids
    perm.data <- data
    perm.data$tx = data$tx[perm] # mixing everything randomly

    ## calculate the mean/median differences on permuted data
    perm.mean.diff <- with(perm.data,
                           mean(obstime[tx == 1]) - mean(obstime[tx == 0]))
    perm.median.diff <- with(perm.data,
                             median(obstime[tx == 1]) - median(obstime[tx == 0]))
    return( c(perm.mean.diff, perm.median.diff) )
}

mmfunc <- function(a) {
suppressMessages(time.summ <- data %>%
            filter(subgroup == a) %>%
             group_by(tx) %>%
             summarise(avg.time = mean(obstime), median.time = median(obstime)))
# observed difference
diff.summ <- time.summ[2,2:3] - time.summ[1,2:3]
group <- data %>%filter(subgroup == a)
set.seed(1)
permuted.stats <- data.frame(t(replicate(nsim, simulate.perm.trial(group))))
colnames(permuted.stats) <- c("mean.diff","median.diff")

## Calculating tail probabilities
tail.prob.mean <- mean(permuted.stats$mean.diff > diff.summ$avg.time)
tail.prob.medi <- mean(permuted.stats$median.diff > diff.summ$median.time)
tail.prob.mean
}

For the second part of the question, we are interested in whether the treatment effect appears to differ across age. We can first get a visualization of the association, by plotting observation time versus age, with two colors representing treatment and control group, and fit loess curve to the two groups. From the plot, we can see that the two lines have overlapping confidence intervals, meaning that the observation time for the two groups does not differ. And as age increases, the trends for both groups are not clear, and both fitted lines have upward and downward trends. We can conclude from the graph that the treatment effect does not differ substantively across age, since we lack statistical evidence of concluding which arm is better for patients across age range. To confirm the preliminary conclusion from the graph, we can calculate MSE and use permutation tests to compare the calculated r^2 from the observation and the permuted test. The r^2 we calculated from our dataset is 0.00995, and in order to know whether this value is large or small, we chose to do permutation tests. The null hypothesis in this question is that the effect of treatment does not differ across age. After doing the procedures, a p-value of 0.96 > 0.05 was obtained, we reject the null that effect of treatment is the same across age. By plotting the original r^2 and the permuted r^2, we can see that 0.00995 is not significantly larger, meaning that there is no strong association between age and treatment effect.

######### making visuals
nsclc %>%
ggplot(aes(x = age, y = obstime, color=as.factor(tx))) +

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

######### calculate p-value for association
fit.null <- lm(obstime ~ 1, data = nsclc) ## no treatment
resids.null <- nsclc$obstime - predict(fit.null) 

calc.assoc.meas <- function(data, null.resid) {
  
 fit.age.perm <- lm(obstime ~ age*as.factor(tx), data=data)
  resids.age.perm <- data$obstime - predict(fit.age.perm)
  MSE.assoc.perm <- 1 - mean(resids.age.perm^2)/mean(null.resid^2) # the r square
  
  return(MSE.assoc.perm)
}
orig.summary <- calc.assoc.meas(nsclc, resids.null)

simulate.perm.trial <- function(data, null.resid){
  
  ## create the permuted data ##
  perm <- sample(1:nrow(data), replace = FALSE)
  perm.data <- data
  perm.data$age <- data$age[perm]
  
  perm.summary <- calc.assoc.meas(data=perm.data, null.resid)
  
  return( perm.summary )
}
nsim <- 1e3
set.seed(1)
permuted.stats <- data.frame(replicate(nsim, simulate.perm.trial(nsclc, resids.null)))
colnames(permuted.stats) <- ("MSE.assoc")
ggplot(permuted.stats, aes(x=MSE.assoc, y=..density..)) +
  geom_density()+
  geom_vline(xintercept=orig.summary, colour="red")

mean(permuted.stats >= orig.summary) # the p-value
## [1] 0.96
